duration of action varies significantly between different insulin types, which influences their role in treatment regimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin degludec\u003C/strong\u003E is an ultra-long-acting insulin analogue with the longest duration of action, lasting up to 42 hours. This extended duration provides more stable glucose control with less variability in absorption, reducing the risk of nocturnal hypoglycaemia. Its long half-life allows for more flexible timing of administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin glargine\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-acting insulin analogue with a duration of action of approximately 24 hours. While it provides good baseline insulin coverage, its duration is significantly shorter than insulin degludec.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin isophane\u003C/strong\u003E is an intermediate-acting insulin with a duration of action of 12-16 hours. Its peak action occurs at 4-6 hours after administration, which can contribute to nocturnal hypoglycaemia when given in the evening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin detemir\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-acting insulin analogue with a duration of action of 18-24 hours. Like insulin glargine, it provides more predictable absorption than insulin isophane but has a shorter duration than insulin degludec.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin aspart\u003C/strong\u003E is a rapid-acting insulin analogue with a duration of action of 3-5 hours. It is designed for mealtime coverage rather than basal insulin requirements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin degludec has the longest duration of action of all available insulin preparations, lasting up to 42 hours.","Ultra-long acting insulins provide more stable glucose control with less risk of nocturnal hypoglycaemia compared to shorter-acting preparations.","Understanding the duration of action of different insulin preparations is crucial for appropriate diabetes management."],"references":["Donnor et al, Insulin- Pharmacology, Therapeutic Regimens and Principles of Intensive Insulin Therapy, Endotext, 2023, https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278938/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-24T22:23:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-20T13:27:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11786"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81061"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":nul